The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Thursday, June 16, 2005 

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta: Calcutta High Court today directed the West Bengal Council for Higher Secondary Education to re-examine the answer scripts of a student, who is unhappy with his marks in English and Bengali.

 Ayan Das, a student of Purulia Ramakrishna Mission, had appeared in last years Higher Secondary examination and scored 926. 

 He had moved court after his Madhayamik examination as well, and after a review got 13 extra marks that helped him get a place among the states top 10. 

 Krishnagar: A 19-year-old girl has accused her boyfriend two years younger than her of rape and lodged a complaint with Ranaghat police in Nadia district. The girl, from a poor farmers family in Taherpur, about 70 km from Calcutta, said she became pregnant and had to undergo an abortion. The accused, Sumon Haldar, a Class X student of Taherpur High School, is on the run.

 Calcutta: Kalpana Sardar, a 30-year-old housewife, was bludgeoned to death with an iron rod allegedly by her brother-in-law Swapan, a CPM activist, at Beliator in Barasat on Wednesday. Police said Kalpana had spurned Swapans indecent overtures, which enraged him. Swapan was arrested with the help of residents.

 Calcutta: State home secretary Amit Kiran Deb was in Delhi on Tuesday to air Bengals views on Bangladesh-related issues ahead of the bilateral talks slated for June 21 and 22. The state government has expressed concern over infiltration, water-sharing and law and order problems on the border, Deb said. 

 Calcutta: A 17-year-old boy was run over by a private bus at Cossipore on Wednesday. Debajyoti Das was hit when he slipped and fell while trying to board the bus. He was taken to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital where he was declared dead. 




